external_knowledge:
- 'deep connection' refers to users who have an active preference (`is_active = 1`);
- 'melodies played' refers to the activity type 'play' (`activity_type = 'play'`);
- 'more than 10 times' refers to the condition `HAVING COUNT(T5.song_id) > 10`.

- "golden melody" refers to the song with the highest average playback duration;
- "captivates the audience the most" refers to the song being played the longest on average;
- "highest quality version" refers to the version of the song with the maximum sample rate multiplied by bit depth.

sql:
SELECT user_id, song_id, play_duration
FROM playback_history
WHERE play_duration > 100;

external_knowledge:
- 'Garden of musical delights' refers to the collection of songs in a playlist;
- 'Flowers that shine the brightest' refers to the most popular songs;
- 'My Favorite Songs' is the name of the playlist.

- "Played the most" refers to the song with the highest total playback duration;
- "Energy level of its genre" refers to the average energy level of the genre to which the song belongs;
- "Size of the playlist it inhabits" refers to the number of songs in the playlist where the song is included.

- "top 5 songs" refers to songs with the highest average playback duration, ranked 1 through 5;
- "longest average playtime" is the average duration of play sessions for each song;
- "cream of the crop from a musical garden" is a metaphor for the most popular or highly regarded songs based on average playtime.

- The "top 5 genres" are determined by the average popularity of the songs within each genre;
- "Admiration" refers to the popularity of the songs, which is a measure of how well the songs are liked or appreciated;
- "Most cherished melody" refers to the song with the highest popularity for each artist.

- "melody master" refers to the user with `user_id = 1`;
- "musical notes" refers to the unique songs identified by `song_id`;
- "personal symphony" refers to the user's playback history.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT song_id) 
FROM playback_history 
WHERE user_id = 1;
